\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 1.	Cognitivism \'97 Are moral judgments capable of truth or falsity? Yes or No\
2.	Theories of truth \'97 If moral judgments do have truth values, in what sense? \
3.	Objectivity \'97 in what ways, if any, does the existence of moral properties depend upon the actual or possible states of mind of intelligent beings?\
4.	Reductionism \'97 Are moral properties reducible to (or do they supervene upon) nonmoral properties?\
5.	Naturalism \'97 Are moral properties natural properties? \
6.	Empiricism \'97 Do we come to know moral facts the same way we come to know the facts of empirical science, or are they revealed by reason or by some special mode of apprehension?\
7.	Bivalence \'97 Does the principle of the excluded middle apply to moral judgments? \
8.	Determinateness \'97 Given whatever procedures we have for assessing moral judgments, how much morality is likely to be determinable? \
9.	Categoricity \'97 Do all rational agents necessarily have some reason to obey moral imperatives?\
10.	Universality \'97 Are moral imperatives applicable to all rational agents, even (should such exist) those that lack a reason to comply with them?\
11.	Assessment of existing moralities \'97 Are present moral beliefs approximately true, or do prevailing moral intuitions in some other sense constitute privileged data?\
12.	Relativism \'97 Does the truth or warrant of moral judgments depend directly upon individually- or socially-adopted norms or practices? \
13.	Pluralism \'97 Is there a uniquely good form of life or a uniquely right moral code?\
