Railton sets up the fact/value distinction as the strongest objection to realism. In its epistemic mode, the objection claims that after all factual, scientific, rational \'93means of adjudication have been deployed\'94 that value disputes can persist (166). Such an objection depends on a notion of reason as merely instrumental, which Railton endorses (166). But he denies Hume\'92s \'93thesis of the practicality of moral judgment\'94 in order to \'93remove the ground of his contrast between facts and values\'94 (170). \
\
Railton argues that values are real on the basis of \'93independence\'94 (the value has \'93certain determinate features independent of whether we think it exists\'94) and \'93feedback\'94 (the ability of us to interact with it and it with us) (172). Railton makes an analogy between value and the external world. The reality of the external world best explains its seeming independence and feedback. \
\
(The fact that values (non-moral values first) seem to exhibit independence and feedback shows that it is real.) \
\
The \'93reduction basis\'94 of a secondary quality like sweetness or desirability is a \'93complex set of relational, dispositional, primary qualities\'94 such that \'93in ordinary circumstances sugar excites a certain gustatory sensation in me\'94 (173). Subjective interests are secondary qualities but do not constitute desirableness. To get desirableness, one has to endow an individual A with \'93unqualified cognitive and imaginative powers, and full factual and nomological information about his physical and psychological constitution, capacities, history, and so on\'94 (174). \
\
Railton sketches a wants/interests mechanism that explains an agent\'92s actions. An agent (Lonnie) used to drink milk when he felt sick while travelling, but comes to drink clear liquids because of the positive feedback (albeit unconscious feedback) he gets from drinking 7-Up. The explanation is that Lonnie\'92s subjective interest (his wants) has come into closer alignment with his objective interest (the desirability of clear liquids). The objective interest is defined as a set of relational facts\
